2026-06-14 | Maximum Twin Sum of a Linked List

	Question
Return the maximum twin sum among all twin pairs.
	Key Insight
In a linked list, accessing the twin node directly is difficult.
So:
1.	Find the middle of the linked list.
2.	Reverse the second half.
3.	Now:
		first half moves forward
		reversed second half moves forward
	and corresponding twin nodes become aligned.
4.	Compute sums pairwise.
5.	Track the maximum.
	Approach
1.	Use slow and fast pointers to find the middle.
2.	Reverse the second half of the list.
3.	Maintain two pointers:
		first = head
		second = reversed half
4.	For each pair:
		maxAns =
		max(maxAns,
		    first->val + second->val)
5.	Move both pointers.
6.	Return maximum answer.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* reverseList(ListNode* head) {
        ListNode* prev = nullptr;
        ListNode* curr = head;
        while(curr) {
            ListNode* nextNode = curr->next;
            curr->next = prev;
            prev = curr;
            curr = nextNode;
        }
        return prev;
    }
    int pairSum(ListNode* head) {
        ListNode* slow = head;
        ListNode* fast = head;
        while(fast && fast->next) {
            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next->next;
        }
        ListNode* secondHalf = reverseList(slow);
        int ans = 0;
        ListNode* first = head;
        ListNode* second = secondHalf;
        while(second) {
            ans = max(ans,
                      first->val + second->val);
            first = first->next;
            second = second->next;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
After reversing the second half, twin nodes appear at the same relative position in two forward-moving lists:
		first half:
		5 → 4
		reversed second half:
		1 → 2
This allows computing every twin sum in a single traversal, achieving O(n) time and O(1) extra space.
